Have no pattern.

School have numerical-integer values. These are results for children from two different countries, of different ages, who may be repeaters.

School %>% separate (Country, Into=C(“France”, “Portugal”), sep=“_“) Note%>% unite(Note, Repeater)

For School, is there a difference between countries in terms of grades? Or is there a difference between repeaters and non-repeaters? The best way to visualise the response correctly is with boxplots.

The country of origin or the fact of being a repeater has no influence on the results.

So, H0 : The country of origin n’a pas une plus grande influence sur les résultats que le fait d’être redoublant. For that, we go use the t-test. Indeed, it can be done for all group sizes with the help of computers and the data will be considered here as normal (the latter being a totally random creation, it is not really the case). t.test(x=Note\(Country, Note\)Repeater, paired=T, alternative=“greater”)

In this case, isn’t very usefull but PCA can be use for répondre à des questions telles que “quels sont les facteurs principaux permettant l’observation du lynx ?” ou encore “quels sont kes facteurs principaux à l’origine de la diminution démographique du lynx?”
